@NODE MENU_LOADPIC "Load picture"
@{b}@{u}Load picture@{uu}@{ub}

This menue opens a file-requester to choose the file to load into XTrace.
XTrace loads these file formats: @{"IFF XTVF" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }, IFF ILBM and available
Datatypes.

If the file has successfully been loaded, a new @{"Picture window" link WIN_PICTURE } opens which
displays the loaded picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_LOADFONT "Load font"
@{b}@{u}Load font@{uu}@{ub}

This menue opens a font-requester to choose the file to load into XTrace.
Datatypes.

If the file has successfully been loaded, a new @{"Picture window" link WIN_PICTURE } opens which
displays the loaded font.

You can use this to create 3D-fonts for Michiel den Outer's "Navigator Titler"
(see @{"FAQ" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FAQ} also).

When you've loaded a font, many other menue items and operator options are
disabled because of much differences between pictures and fonts.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SAVEPIC "Save picture as"
@{b}@{u}Save picture / Save picture as@{uu}@{ub}

Saves @{"IFF XTVF" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } files.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_EXPORTPIC "Export picture (to clipboard)"
@{b}@{u}Export picture (to clipboard)@{uu}@{ub}

This very important menue of XTrace allows the exportation of bitmaps and
vector pictures in @{"formats" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS}, which can be processed/loaded by paint
(for example DPaint, XiPaint) or DTP (for example PageStream) programs.
A window pops up, in which different @{"settings" link WIN_CHOOSETOEXPORT} can be changed or
choosen from.

Some exporters (@{"Navigator Titler Logo" link WIN_EXPNLOGO}, @{"Navigator Titler Font" link WIN_EXPNFONT}
@{"DXF 3D" link WIN_EXPDXF3D})cogent requires additional particulars which will be interrogate after
the format selection.

Pictures can also be exported directly to the @{"clipboard" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }. This way they can
be used by other programs.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLOSEPIC "Close picture"
@{b}@{u}Close picture@{uu}@{ub}

This menue removes the picture from memory. If the picture has been changed
a requester pops up to remind you to save the picture or cancel the 'Close
picture' action.
The Closegadget on the picture window has the same effect as this menue.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DELETEFILES "Delete files"
@{b}@{u}Delete files@{uu}@{ub}

Well, this menue deletes selected files. A security check is done.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_READCLIP "Read picture from clipboard"
@{b}@{u}Read picture from clipboard@{uu}@{ub}

This function allows you to load @{"IFF ILBM" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS } and @{"IFF XTVF" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } pictures into
XTrace from the @{"clipboard" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }.

The Listviewgadget shows all 256 clipboards, with Unit-number, Loadable,
Type, Size in bytes and its Name. XTrace can load the clipboard if L
(Loadable) is marked with a "*",

It is possible to specify the to be loaded Unit with the number-gadget and
the unit-number.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_WRITECLIP "Write picture to clipboard"
@{b}@{u}Write picture to clipboard@{uu}@{ub}

This menue saves @{"IFF XTVF" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } pictures to the clipboard.
These clipboard files can be loaded in a second running XTrace.

The Listviewgadget shows all 256 clipboards, with Unit-number, Loadable,
Type, Size in bytes and its Name. XTrace can load the clipboard if L
(Loadable) is marked with a "*",

It is possible to specify the to be loaded Unit with the number-gadget and
the unit-number.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FREECLIP "Free clipboard"
@{b}@{u}Free clipboard@{uu}@{ub}

This function deletes files saved to the @{"clipboards" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_HELP "Help"
@{b}@{u}Help@{uu}@{ub}

Opens the main XTrace AmigaGuide® help-file, as long as a documentations
is installed and the right path has been set correctly in
@{"Settings / Paths & Patterns" link MENU_SETPATHPATT}.

For further information please read the chapter @{"Using Online-Help" link ONLINEHELP }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_PRGINFO "Program info"
@{b}@{u}Program info@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item shows the memory usage of XTrace at the moment and the name
of the ARexx-port. Moreover, you can see how much RAM was allocated at maximum
(Peak values).

@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SYSINFO "System info"
@{b}@{u}System info@{uu}@{ub}

This function shows the memory usage of XTrace at the moment, how much
memory there is still available and which CPU & chips are in the Amiga®
XTrace is running.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_ABOUTXTRACE "About XTrace"
@{b}@{u}About XTrace@{uu}@{ub}

A window pops up which shows informations concerning XTrace:
Copyright-, Disclaimer-, Shareware-, Distribution- and Register-
informations, as well as informations about the computer used to develop
XTrace, acknowledgements and dedications.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_ABOUTKEY "About key"
@{b}@{u}About Key@{uu}@{ub}

This window only pops up if you have @{"registered" link XTrace_Introduction.guide/REGISTER } XTrace.
It will show infos about your personal keyfile.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_QUIT "Quit"
@{b}@{u}Quit@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item leaves XTrace. A security requester asks for confirmation.
If there are still unsaved pictures open or changed settings which have
not been saved yet, a security requester pops up asking you to either
save the picture/settings or to cancel the "Quit"-requester.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_LOADEDPL "Loaded pictures list"
@{b}@{u}Loaded pictures list@{uu}@{ub}

Opens / closes the "Loaded pictures list" window.

This windows opens in an async manner, in order to continue your work
with XTrace. Just put it to the background.

It lists all opened pictures and if their picture parts (bitmap/vector part)
are available and have been changed. The list is udated any time when you
change, save or close a picture.

If you want this window to be opened automatically when you start XTrace
and its position remembered, change the settings in
@{"Settings / Permanent windows" link MENU_SETPERMWINS}. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_LOG "Log window"
@{b}@{u}Log window@{uu}@{ub}

Opens / closes the "Log window".

This windows opens in an async manner, in order to continue your work
with XTrace. Just put it to the background.

It lists additional information about your work with XTrace. These information
can be saved with @{"Save log" link MENU_SAVELOG} or cleared (@{"Clear log" link MENU_CLEARLOG}).

If you want this window to be opened automatically when you start XTrace
and its position remembered, change the settings in
@{"Settings / Permanent windows" link MENU_SETPERMWINS}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_PENDISPLAY "Pen display"
@{b}@{u}Pen display@{uu}@{ub}

This menue opens / closes the "Pen display" window.

This windows opens in an async manner, in order to continue your work with
XTrace. Just put it to the background.

This window will be opened too, if you select the eyedropper symbol in the
@{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS}. With the selected eyedropper tool and the left mouse button
pressed you can read color informations in the PenDisplay window below the
eyedropper tool.

These informations are as follows:

Pen     - The pen-number of this color. This number is important if you
          want to change the color values with @{"Edit palette" link MENU_EDITPICPAL }.

Red,
Green,
Blue    - The @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } - values of this color.

Hue
Satur.
Brigh.  - The @{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } - values of this color.

Gray    - The gray value to be used to display the picture in the Picture
          window.

Real    - The real color of the pixel under the eydropper.

Name,
Match   - The name of the color, as it is available from the internal list.
          This list only contains a range of colors/names, as this list can
          not include all existing colors. The Match-value tells you how
          similar the shown colorname matches the real color.

If you want this window to be opened automatically when you start XTrace
and its position remembered, change the settings in
@{"Settings / Permanent windows" link MENU_SETPERMWINS}. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLEARLOG "Clear log"
@{b}@{u}Clear log@{uu}@{ub}

Clears the log which you can see in the @{"Log window" link MENU_LOG}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SAVELOG "Save log"
@{b}@{u}Save log@{uu}@{ub}

Saves the log which you can see in the @{"Log window" link MENU_LOG} to a selectable file
as plain ASCII.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLEANUP "Cleanup windows"
@{b}@{u}Cleanup windows@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item allows you to cleanup all open picture windows. XTrace
tries to not overlap the windows. If there isn't enough place, the windows
will be placed to their standard positions.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLEANUPMIN "Minimize & Cleanup windows"
@{b}@{u}Minimize & Cleanup windows@{uu}@{ub}

Like @{"Cleanup windows" link MENU_CLEANUP }, only this time the windows are minimized to their
smallest size before they are re-positioned.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_INFO "Info"
@{b}@{u}Info@{uu}@{ub}

This menue function displays informations about the actual active picture,
like path and filename and if the picture has already been traced the
following infos :

 - the type of the picture (picture or font)
 - the size of the Bitmap.- and of the vector-picture
 - der @{"Bitmap storage type" link MENU_SETSTORTYPE }
 - @{"Color-Type" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } and @{"aspect" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } about the Bitmap.- and Vector-picture
 - @{"Used Colors" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }
 - number of @{"objects" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }, @{"vectors" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } and the number of these
   for this picture
 - number of chars at a loaded font
 - used memory for the actual picture
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPANNO "Display annotation"
@{b}@{u}Display annotation@{uu}@{ub}

This menue shows you comments and annotations of the actual active picture.
These comments are included in IFF ILBM and @{"IFF XTVF" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } pictures.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_COPYPIC "Copy picture"
@{b}@{u}Copy picture@{uu}@{ub}

The complete active picture (with its vector datas etc.) is copied and
displayed in a new Picture window.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLOSEBITMAPPART "Close bitmap part"
@{b}@{u}Close bitmap part@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith, you can free the bitmap part of the active picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CLOSEVECTORPART "Close vector part"
@{b}@{u}Close vector part@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith, you can free the vector part of the active picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_REMUNUSED "Remove unused colors"
@{b}@{u}Remove unused colors@{uu}@{ub}

This function removes unused colors from a picture. Depending on the
menue item choosen this occurs as follows:

@{b}Bitmap picture@{ub} 

The maximum possible number of colors per picture is defined by its depth.
A depth of e.g. 5 means 2^5 = 32 possible colors. If this maximum number of
available colors is not used by the picture, this menue item allows you to
remove all unused colors of the 32. Pens with identical @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } values will
be resumed to one pen. The used colors will be moved together on the first
positions of the color palette and unused memory will be given free.

This works only, if this picture uses the @{"Color-Type" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } palette.
Otherwise no colors can be removed.

@{b}Vector picture@{ub} 

This menue item joins pens with identical @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colorvalues to one pen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_COALESCECOLORS "Coalesce colors"
@{b}@{u}Coalesce colors@{uu}@{ub}

With this function it is possible to join resemble colors and to remove
unused colors of the picture.

By coalescing of resemble colors, the picture quality (depend on the parameter)
will be slightly impaired only, but several colors will be set to one color
value and larger homogeneous areas arise (faster tracing, less complex vector
pictures) and the bitmap picture will need fewer memory.

The colors of a vector picture will be coalesced only (and unused are removed),
ie. the operator will not change to size or complexity of the picture.

With the parameter "Max. distance" you can set the maximal distance of two
colors which can be joined. The distance is measured in percent as to the
diagonal of space of the RGB cube. Good values are 0.5 - 5 %.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_MAKEPENTRANS "Make pen transparent"
@{b}@{u}Make pen transparent@{uu}@{ub}

With this function, you can make a certain pen of a vector picture
transparent. This means, when you use this picture in, for example, a
DTP programm, the background behind this picture will be shine through
the areas, which was colored with the pen before.

You can select the pen to make transparent with the "Pen to make transparent"
gadgets.

You can also use this function several times to make more pens transparent.

@{b}Attention: Should you discover problems with this function, like, for
example corrupted pictures or crashs, @{"trace" link MENU_TRACE } the picture again and
use this operator once again.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_REMOVEPEN "Remove pen"
@{b}@{u}Remove pen@{uu}@{ub}

With this operator you can remove objects with a selectable color. It's not
ensured, that holes stay holes like @{"Make pen transparent" link MENU_MAKEPENTRANS}, the objects
will only removed.

You can select the pen to remove with the "Pen to remove" gadgets.
You can also use this function several times to remove more pens.

@{b}Use this operator with care and use the "Display..." gadgets after the operator
is ready to display the results before you select "Ok" !@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CONVCOLOR "Convert color"
@{b}@{u}Convert color@{uu}@{ub}

This menue allows you to change the @{"Color-Type" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } of the active picture.
The Color-type can be changed with the "Type"-gadget, the number of pens
with the "Pennumber"-gadget.

The method to be used to convert color picture to grayscale or black/white
pictures can be selected/changed in @{"Settings" link MENU_SETGRAY }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPHISTO "Display histograms"
@{b}@{u}Display histograms@{uu}@{ub}

This menue show the color histograms of the active picture.

Additional to the 'normal' histogram ("Palette"), separate histograms for the
red, green and blue parts as well as brightness and saturation parts of the
colors are displayed.

If the left mouse button is pressed, when you move the mouse pointer
over the "Palette" histogram, the following informations are shown:

Pen     - The pen-number of this color. This number is necessary if you
          want to change the color values in the @{"Edit palette" link MENU_EDITPICPAL }.

Number  - Number of pixel used by this pen.

Part    - % of this pen used in the picture.

Real    - The real color of the pixel.

Name,
Match   - The name of the color, as it is available from the internal list.
          This list only contains a range of colors/names, as this list can
          not include all existing colors. The Match-value tells you how
          similar the shown colorname matches the real color.

The cycle gadget named "Histogram type" is used to decide either to display
the histgrams normal or accumulated. With the accumulated histogram you can
find out, if the histogram is @{"equalized" link MENU_EQUAHISTO }.

With the cycle gadget "Color type" you can switch the colors of the histo-
grams between black and the gray tones used for picture displaying.
Herewith you can also display histograms correctly, if one or more gray
tones of the histograms are the same as the screen background color.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_STRCHISTO "Stretch histogram"
@{b}@{u}Stretch histogram@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can stretch the histogram, this means for examples if the
active picture have 256 gray scales and only the pens 130 - 140 are used,
you can not or bardly distinguish these color, you see only a
monochromatical gray area.

With "Stretch histogram" the used color values are stretched over the all
available color values, the contrast will be maximized.

You can display the histogram before and after "Stretch histogram" with
@{"Display histogram" link MENU_DISPHISTO}. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_EQUAHISTO "Equalize histogram"
@{b}@{u}Equalize histogram@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can equalize the histogram, this means often used and similar
color values occur in the picture will be seperated wider.
Thereby modest brightness differences will be emphasized clearly.

You can display the histogram before and after "Stretch histogram" with
@{"Display histogram" link MENU_DISPHISTO}. 
You are going to discover, that the accumulated histogram pass from below
left to above right, what means, that every color tone roughly exists equal
times respectively seperated from similar gray tones, because of the height
(hence the number of pixels with this gray tone) of a histogram entry 
defines the color range, covered by the entry.

See also @{"Adaptive histogram equalization" link MENU_ADAPTHISTEQUAL}.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_ADAPTHISTEQUAL "Adaptive histogram equalization"
@{b}@{u}Adaptive histogram equalization@{uu}@{ub}

With this function it is possible to equalize an histogram like with
@{"Equalize histogram" link MENU_EQUAHISTO}. But, for example, an existing large background or
dominant colorscales will not affect the whole picture. Thus, small, 
interesting structures can be made visible much simplier than with
@{"Equalize histogram" link MENU_EQUAHISTO}.

"Arraysize" is the size (e.g. length of the edge) of quadratic fields. In
every one of this fields an normal histogram equalization (and a little
bit more) will be performed. This parameter should have the size (or slightly
more) of the interesting structures or the areas of dominante colorscales.
Additionaly, a field should contain at least so much pixels like the number
of picture's colors.

Because of the equalized histogram of every field will be calculated also out
of neighbour fields and fields on the border doesn't have all of these neigh-
bours colors must be defined for these fields. For these fields you can use
the at the border mirrored contents of the picture ('Mirror border' enabled)
or a color ('Mirror border' off, color is selectable with 'Outside color'
(@{"Choose color" LINK WIN_CHOOSECOLOR} or @{"Choose grayscale" LINK WIN_CHOOSEGRAYSCALE})).
These color can be also calculated with 'Determine outside color'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_EDITPICPAL "Edit palette"
@{b}@{u}Edit palette@{uu}@{ub}

This function enables you to change the color palette of a picture, either
a vector picture or if it's a bitmap picture, with the @{"Color-Type" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } palette.
This depends on the choosen menue item.

Functions of the Edit palette window:

With the slider on right top side and the palette gadget below you can
change the active pen.

The gadgets "Copy", "Swap" and "Reset" allows you to copy, swap pens (like
any color program on the Amiga® ;-)) or reset @{b}all@{ub} pens to their original
colors.

The colorwheel and the gradientslider are used to change the colors of the
active pen according to the @{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

The 3 sliders "Red", "Green" and "Blue" in the middle of the window are
used to change the colors of the active pen according to the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

"Real" shows the real color of this pen. "Name" is the name of the color,
like it is used in the internal list. The Match-value tells you how similar
the shown colorname matches the real color.

The popup-gadget besides the name opens a requester window with all
available colornames (@{"Color names" link WIN_COLORNAMES }).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_GLOBCOLCON "Global color control"
@{b}@{u}Global color control@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can, in contrast to @{"Edit palette" link MENU_EDITPICPAL }, change all color values
together according to certain schemes either of a bitmap or vector picture.
This depends on the choosen menue item.

This is possible, because of using so called "color curves" displayed in
4 areas, indicated by "Red", "Green", "Blue" and "Saturation". The curves
are really tables which map every red, green, blue or saturation value
to a new output value.
Herewith for example, you can change the brightness seperately for red,
green and blue or the saturation for complete color values.
The default setting (diagonal line, from lower left to upper right) map 
every value to an identical output value, i.e. no changes will be made.

Description of functions :

With the "Name" gadget you can name the curves. It is useful, if you want
to save these curves. Additional remarks can be stored with the "Remark"
gadget.

The checkbox gadgets are used to en-/disable the curve below the gadget.
You can not edit the curve by mouse of change by functions if the curves
has been disabled. It is useful, if you want to change for example only the
brightness of the red curve.

If you process bitmap pictures with the @{"Color-Typ" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } Gray the saturation
curve is not available, because of the intensity (brightness) is equal to the
saturation. It is also impossible to en-/disabled curves because of red,
green and blue values must be equal at gray.

The color curves are shown in the curve gadgets and can be edited also by
mouse. If you edit one of the red, green or blue curve the other enabled
curves, exept the saturation curve, will be changed in the same way.

The @{b}active@{ub} curves can be set to the default state (diagonal line) with
"Init" and with "Invert" you can negate (to invert the colors) them. With
"Smooth" you can smooth for example hand-drawed curves.

With the "Brightness", "Contrast" and "Saturation" gadgets you can change
the brightness, contrast resp. the saturation. The arrow up rise the degree
of alternation, the arrow down degrade the same one. Repercussions can be
seen at the curves.

The "Gamma" gadgets can be used to correct the @{b}active@{ub} RGB curves by a gamma
value, what means, depend of the "Gamma value" the contrast of darker color
parts will be increased stronger the the brighter ones.
Thereby a special of the human eyes will be equalized, which can differ
similar dark color tones more worse the bright tones. So if you use gamma
correction, darker details of the picture can be differ but the brighter
details will not be merged.
The arrow up rise and the arrow down lowers the intensity of correction.

With the "Gamma value" gadgets the intensity of correction can be changed.
A normal value is 2.2 - 2.3, but can be changed between 0.1 and 10.0.
Values greater than 1.0 effect the effect described above, values smaller
than 1.0 effect the oppsite.

You can change the step sizes, used at the work with the arrow gadgets with
the "Step size" gadgets. Thereby for example you can change the brightness
quicker, i.e. 1 click on an arrow-up gadget at a step size of 8 is equal
to 8 clicks on the same gadget at step size 1.

With "New curves" @{b}all@{ub} curves will be initialized new and with "Load curves"
and "Save curves" you can load/save all curves into a file.

The appearance of the window and the functions was inspirated by HamLab Plus
by J. E. Hanway.

@{b}Please note, that the file format of the color curves has been changed
with XTrace v2.00. Please see the @{"history" LINK XTrace_Appendix.guide/HISTORY} or @{"'FileFormatConverter'" LINK FILEFORMATCONVERTER} for
more information.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_INVERT "Invert"
@{b}@{u}Invert@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can invert the picture (bitmap or vektor, depends on menue),
this means to generate the negative.

Grayscales and B/W are inverted normally (Black <-> White), colors will
be inverted to the opposed color regarding to the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } color space.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SCALE "Scale"
@{b}@{u}Scale@{uu}@{ub}

Allows you to scale a picture. The change can be done by pixel (absolute)
or on a percental basis.

If "LockAspect" is enabled, then the @{"aspect" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } of picture will not be
changed when scaled.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_BORDER "Border process"
@{b}@{u}Border process@{uu}@{ub}

This function removes or adds borders of pictures.

In the upper part of the window you can specify if the borders on the
left, right, upper or lower side should be removed. Only those borders
will be removed which do have the color shown in "Pen". The color can
be @{"changed" link WIN_CHOOSEPEN } by clicking the PopUp-gadget.

In the lower part of the window you can specify if a border should be
added. The size and pen for the border (again left, right, up, lower)
can be changed.

The other 4 adjust-gadgets enables you to transfer the border size to
all borders. The @{"aspect" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } of the picture will be taken into consideration.
This way the borders on all sides of the picture will be the same size.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FILTERSEQ "Apply digital filter sequence"
@{b}@{u}Apply digital filter sequence@{uu}@{ub}

The digital filter is one of the strongest function in XTrace. The digital
filter can smooth borders, emboss the picture, smooth the contrast ...

Herewith it is also possible to apply several filters after each other
to the picture.

@{b}General@{ub} 

A filter consists generally in a quadratic matrix with odd height and width.
It contains matrix values for the different pixels of the picture. There
is also a "Divider" value (in general the sum of all matrix values) and
a "Bias" value as offset for the calculated result.

XTrace uses 2 filter types, linear and non-linear, and 4 filter sizes,
1x1, 3x3, 5x5 and 7x7. 

With @{b}linear filters@{ub} the filtermatrix is applied to all pixels of the
picture. Where the actual pixel is the center of the matrix. The color
values of the pixels under the matrix are multiplied by the values of the
matrix. The sum of these products will be devided by the "Divider"-value
and the result is added to the "Bias"-value. This new color value is
applied to the actual pixel. This new color value must be inside the
possible color range, if not the minimum or maximum possible color value
will used.

Hence, it is the calculation of a weighted mean. With a "Bias" value un-
equal 0 a result range outside the normal calculated range can be used.

Example : A simple rectangle-lowpassfilter uses values of 1 only. Bias
          equals 0 and the divider must be calculated. This filter removes
          noise from the picture but the it looks blurred.

With @{b}non-linear@{ub} filters the filtermatrix is applied to all pixels of the
picture. Where the actual pixel is the center of the matrix. The brightness
values of the pixels under the matrix are ordered inside a list if the
actual value of the matrix equal to 1. According the the rank, either the
first value of the list (minimum), or the mean value of the list (median)
or the last value of the list (maximum) will be used as new actual pen and
applied to the actual pixel.

Matrix values can only be 0 or 1.

Example : A simple mediancut-filter uses values of 1 only. The rank is
          median, hence the name. This filter removes low noise from the
          picture without affecting other parts of the picture (not blurred
          as with the linear lowpassfilter).
          This filter is also used as base by the @{"Remove isolated pixels" LINK MENU_REMISOLATEDPIXELS}
          operator.

@{b}Filter sequences and filter sets@{ub}

Single filters can be put together to filter sequences and/or filter sets.
Filter sequences are applied by applying two or more filters @{b}one by one
on a picture@{ub}, whereby each filter processes the whole picture. This
combination of single filters to filter sequences can be done in the
"Apply digital filter sequence" window and is described below.

Filter sets are applied by applying two or more filters @{b}on each pixel of the
picture at the same time@{ub}. The new color/grayscale of the pixel will set to
the minimum, maximum or euklidean distance of the results of each single
filter. Filter sets are called in the literature often as "Template matching
operators". The combination of single filters to filter sets is described
in the @{"Edit filter" LINK WIN_EDITFILTER} window.

For easier understanding, filter sets even called filters in the following
text.

@{b}Creation of sequences@{ub} 

You can create filter sequences out of one or more filters or filter sets.
Sequences with only one filter allow, to apply filters traditionally, but
sequences with more than one filter/filtersequences can create interesting
effects.

With the 'Apply digital filter sequence' window you can create such 
sequences :

The sequence list is shown left. Each filter in the sequence is displayed
with name, number of single filters (for filter sets, 'normal' filters have
one singe filter) and size (1, 3, 5, 7). If a filter set contains filters
of different sizes, a '-' and the minimal and maximal sizes are displayed.

With the arrows beside, you can, if you have more than one filter in the
list, move the selected filter up/down or to top/bottom.

With the "Name" gadget you can name your sequences, also the name of 
supplied sequences is shown here.  Additional remarks can be stored
with the "Remark" gadget.

The "Add ..." gadget can be used to append a filter to the actual list.
Therefore a @{"Edit filter" link WIN_EDITFILTER } will be pop up.

With "Add saved ..." you can load a ready-made filter, who will also be
append to the actual list. 

The gadgets "Insert ..." and "Insert saved .." has the same functions
like the "Add ..." and "Add saved ..." gadgets, but the new filter will 
be inserted in front of the actual selected filter inside the list.

With the "Edit ..." gadget you can edit the actual selected filter.
Therefore the @{"Edit filter" link WIN_EDITFILTER } will be pop up.

The "Edit only ..." gadget is included to change or create filters without
take up these ones into the actual list.

With "Remove" you can kill the selected filter, "Copy" copies the selected
filter and insert this one in front of the actual position.

To use a filter it is necessary to specify what to do with pixels outside
of the picture. In this situation parts of the filter will apply outside
of the picture. The resulting picture will be wrong, thus XTrace offers two
ways to avoid this. Either, the mirroed border of the picture can be used
("Mirror border" on) a color ("Mirror border" off) can be choosen with the
"Outside color" gadgets, which occurs often on the picture border. It is
also possible to calculate a matching color with the "Determine outside color"
gadget. In case you've no filters in the list, or only filters with a size of
1×1, no such additional border is needed and all these gadgets will be
disabled.

With the 4 gadgets below you can create a new sequence, load a sequence,
append a sequence at the actual sequence or save the actual sequence.

@{b}Supplied filters@{ub} 

The effects of most of the supplied filters are difficult to describe.
Best is to try them and observe the results carefully.

Emboss#?        - like chiseled in stone
Erosion#?       - smooth dark image parts
Dilatation#?    - smooth white image parts
Laplace#?       - edge detection
LowPass#?       - noise filter
MedianCut#?     - noise filter
Negative        - negative

@{b}Supplied sequences@{ub} 

There were opening and closing sequences with the sizes 3x3 and 5x5 as well
as a relief sequence supplied.

Opening contains a erosion filter followed by a dilatations filter.
With this combination, disorders like isolated pixels, small structures
and growths can be removed. The disorders have to be smaller than the
erosion matrix.

Closing contains a dilatation filter followed by a erosion filter.
With this combination, you can close small gaps.

Opening and Closing can be used cardinally with pictures with all
@{"Color-Typ" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY}es, but most they generate only good results 
with B/W pictures.

Relief contains two opposite emboss filters, therefore a relief will be
created, where only the borders of objects appear higher or lower than
the object.

For more informations concerning digital filters please check literature
about it.

@{b}Please note, that the file format of the filter sequences and filters has
been changed with XTrace v2.00. Please read the @{"history" LINK XTrace_Appendix.guide/HISTORY} or @{"'FileFormatConverter'" LINK FILEFORMATCONVERTER}
for more information.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_THINNING "Thinning"
@{b}@{u}Thinning@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith it is possible, to create the skeletton, this means the median
of all objects. So the objects can be represented abstracted.

If the gadget "Repeat until complete thinning" is checked, the picture will
be thinned until the skeletton has been reached.

If you have deactivated this option, you can select the number of passes
per pen with the gadgets "Passes". If the skeletton reached before the
number of passes has been processed, the thinning process will be stopped.

With the "Background pen" gadgets you can selected the background color,
this means the color of objects which will not be thinned.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_EDGEDETECT "Edge detection"
@{b}@{u}Edge detection@{uu}@{ub}

This operator is only available for bitmap pictures with the @{"Color-Typ" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }
'B/W' or 'Gray'.

Herewith, it is possible to detect all edges (crossings between areas
of different gray intensity) of objects in the picture.

With 'Radius' you can select the radius of the Marr-Hildreth filter, used
for edge detection. According to a larger value, objects has to be larger
to detect their edges, ie. noise and smaller objects will be not/fewer
detected, the slower the process will be.
Hence, the radius is the range of detection.

'Treshhold' is a measurement for the minimal width of edges to be detected.
Standard is 5, this value produces in the most cases good results. But when
'ghostedges' (means edges in the result picture at places where are no 
edges in the source picture) appears try to increase this value and when
edges contain gaps you can decrease this value.

You can use 'Result' to define the color of the edges and the background 
in the resulting picture.

Because of this operator uses a @{"digital filter" link MENU_FILTERSEQ} it is necessary to specify
what to do with pixels outside of the picture, because while processing pixels
at the border of the picture parts of the filter will apply outside of
the picture. These "pixels" can be set to the values of the pixels inside the
picture mirrored on the border ('Mirror border' on) or to a fixed color
('Mirror border' off). This color can be set with 'Outside color (RGB)'.
For facilitation, you can also calculate a matching color with 'Determine
outside color'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_EDGEENHANCE "Edge enhancement"
@{b}@{u}Edge enhancement{uu}@{ub}

Herewith, it is possible to enhance all edges (crossings between areas
of different gray intensity) of objects in the picture.

With 'Alpha' you can select the amplify factor for the operator. Good values
are 0.6 - 0.9. 0.0 means no enhancement, 1.0 full enhancement.

Because of this operator uses a @{"digital filter" link MENU_FILTERSEQ} it is necessary to specify
what to do with pixels outside of the picture, because while processing pixels
at the border of the picture parts of the filter will apply outside of
the picture. These "pixels" can be set to the values of the pixels inside the
picture mirrored on the border ('Mirror border' on) or to a fixed color
('Mirror border' off). This color can be set with 'Outside color (RGB)'.
For facilitation, you can also calculate a matching color with 'Determine
outside color'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_REMISOLATEDPIXELS "Remove isolated pixels"
@{b}@{u}Remove isolated pixels@{uu}@{ub}

This operator makes it possible to remove isolated pixels, that means pixels
which are injured because of their color.

With "Treshhold" you can set how much the color of a pixel can differ from the
average color of its environment, @{u}without@{uu} classifying it as isolated. The
distance is measured in percent as to the diagonal of space of the RGB cube.

"Filtersize" can be used to set the size of the examined environment of each
pixel.

Because of this operator uses a @{"digital filter" link MENU_FILTERSEQ} it is necessary to specify
what to do with pixels outside of the picture, because while processing pixels
at the border of the picture parts of the filter will apply outside of the
picture. These "pixels" can be set to the values of the pixels inside the
picture mirrored on the border ('Mirror border' on) or to a fixed pen ('Mirror
border' off). This pen can be set with 'Outside pen (RGB)'. For facilitation,
you can also calculate a matching pen with 'Determine outside pen'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CHASPECT "Change aspect"
@{b}@{u}Change aspect@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item changes the @{"aspect" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } of a picture.

If you don't know which aspect you need, but the ScreenMode, you can select
it with the "ScreenMode"-Gadget.

If you click on the "Correct for monitor dimensions" gadget, then the aspect
of standard monitors (13:9) is set accordingly.
The best is if you leave this gadget checked.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_CHDPI "Change DPI & real sizes"
@{b}@{u}Change DPI & real sizes@{uu}@{ub}

Enables you to change the real size of a picture and the resolution (dpi),
as it is used in DTP programs

If you change a value, all other 4 values are changed automatically.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_TRACE "Trace"
@{b}@{u}Trace@{uu}@{ub}

This is the main function of XTrace. It transforms (Tracing) the active
bitmap picture into a vector picture. You can select different options
which enables XTrace to speed up its tracing:

Use Bytemap       - Copies the complete picture into an internal buffer,
                    called ByteMap ((Bitmap storage type ByteMap; @{"Glossar" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }).
                    The different pixels can be accessed much faster this
                    way. When the tracing is finished the buffer will be
                    released again.
                    The "If possible" gadget, allows you to only use this
                    option if there is enough free memory, as this option
                    needs a lot of memory.

Use LineHistogram - Creates for every pixel line of the picture an optimized
                    histogram, which allows to trace the picture faster,
                    especially if areas of certain colors only occur at
                    isolated ranges. The "If possible" gadget has the same
                    function as in the option above.

Display Traces    - Herewith, you can choose if the tracing should be displayed
                    or not. If you disable this option, the tracing speed will
                    be a little bit higher.
              
When you have finished selecting the options, the @{"Trace window" link WIN_TRACE }
pops up.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SELAREA "Process selected area"
@{b}@{u}Process selected area@{uu}@{ub}

The submenue of this menue contains functions to process the area, marked
with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame".

You can @{"copy" link MENU_COPYSELAREA } the selected area or @{"fill" link MENU_FILLSELAREA } it with a color.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_COPYSELAREA " Copy selected area"
@{b}@{u}Process selected area / Copy selected area@{uu}@{ub}

Copies the area (marked with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame") into a new
@{"Picture Window" link WIN_PICTURE}. To dirrerentiate between the 2 pictures, the filename 
of the new one is preceeded by a "C_" (C_ut).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FILLSELAREA " Fill selected area"
@{b}@{u}Process selected area / Fill Selected Area@{uu}@{ub}

Fills the selected area (marked with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame")
with a @{"selectable" link WIN_CHOOSEPEN } pen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPLAY "Display"
@{b}@{u}Display@{uu}@{ub}

The submenue of this menue contains functions to display the active picture
(bitmap or vector, depends on menue) with @{"grayscales" link MENU_DISPGRAY } or @{"colors" link MENU_DISPCOLOR }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPGRAY " Gray"
@{b}@{u}Display / Gray@{uu}@{ub}

The active picture (either bitmap or vector, depends on menue) will be
displayed on an own screen in grayscales. The parameters of this screen
are @{"selectable" link MENU_SETPICDISP }.

If there are more grayscales in the picture as are diplayable on the screen
similar grayscales will be used.
How these grayscales are calculated is selectable in @{"Settings" link MENU_SETGRAY }.

You can leave the screen by hitting any key or clicking the mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPCOLOR " Color"
@{b}@{u}Display / Color@{uu}@{ub}

The active picture (either bitmap or vector, depends on menue) will be
displayed on an own screen in color. The parameters of this screen are
@{"selectable" link MENU_SETPICDISP}. 

If there are more colors in the picture as are diplayable on the screen
similar colors will be used.

You can leave the screen by hitting any key or clicking the mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPLAYSEL "Display selected area"
@{b}@{u}Display selected area@{uu}@{ub}

The submenue of this menue contains functions to display area, marked
with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame" with @{"grayscales" link MENU_DISPGRAY } or @{"colors" link MENU_DISPCOLOR }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPSGRAY " Gray"
@{b}@{u}Display selected area / Gray@{uu}@{ub}

The selected area (marked with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame") of the
active picture will be displayed on an own screen in grayscales. The
parameters of this screen are @{"selectable" link MENU_SETPICDISP }.

If there are more grayscales in the picture as are diplayable on the screen
similar grayscales will be used.
How these grayscales are calculated is selectable in @{"Settings" link MENU_SETGRAY }.

You can leave the screen by hitting any key or clicking the mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DISPSCOLOR " Color"
@{b}@{u}Display selected area / Color@{uu}@{ub}

The selected area (marked with the @{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS } symbol "frame") of the
active picture will be displayed on an own screen in colors. The
parameters of this screen are @{"selectable" link MENU_SETPICDISP }.

If there are more colors in the picture as are diplayable on the screen
similar colors will be used.

You can leave the screen by hitting any key or clicking the mouse.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SUPNOISE "Supress noise"
@{b}@{u}Supress noise@{uu}@{ub}

This function removes small objects, which may appear after you've traced
a noisy bitmap picture.

Different noise-suppress types are available:

"Type to use"-Gadget : Use sizes and area
                       Use sizes only
                       Use area only

Depending on the type used, only some of the following options are
available:

The "Maximum X size"-gadget sets the maximum horizontal size of the
@{"objects" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY} to be removed. The "Maximum Y size" -gadget does 
the same for the maximum vertical size.

The "Maximum area"-gadget sets the maximum area of the @{"objects" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY} to be
removed. Use this option for example, to remove small objects.

The values depend form the size of the picture. Values of 1% for the
"Maximum X size" and "Maximum Y Size" and 9 "Maximum area" are acceptable
values. Best is to try with every picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SLOPE "Slope"
@{b}@{u}Slope@{uu}@{ub}

This function removes jaggy lines from the traced picture. Normally these
lines will be traced into many vector lines, but the slope function only
makes @{b}one@{ub} vector line of this or transforms a curve into @{"Bézier curves" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY}.
These lines look much "cleaner" and less jaggy. The vectorized picture will
also use less memory.

6 values set the conversion of lines and curves:

With "Min. correlation" you define, which minimal correlation coefficent,
calculated out of several, successively placed vectors, is needed to define
these vectors as line. 100 % means, the points have to be exactly on the
line, at 0 % the position if vectors is alike.
This parameter is needed to distinguish between lines and curves.
A good value is 50 %, but this value is @{b}extremly@{ub} depend of the picture.

The "Correlation accuracy" gadgets sets the accuracy of the correlation
calculation. At a value of 1, only the begin and the end of a vector are used
for the calculation, at 2, one interpolated point between begin and end point
is additional used for the calculation, at a value of 3 two interpolated points
and so on. The standard value is 5. A higher value will therefore produce a
better representation of the vector for the calculation.

"Convert 'stairs' to lines" transforms jaggy lines into less jaggy
lines (less 'stairs').

The "Tolerance"-gadget sets the number of pixels the new line can vary from
the original jaggy line. This option is necessary because most paint
programs do use different algorithms to draw lines, this complicates the
analysis of these lines. Good values range from 2 to 4.

The "Min. length of lines"-gadget sets the minimum length of the lines to
be converted. This way, only longer lines will be converted to vector lines.
All other lines (shorter) will be converted to Bézier curves.
Best values range from 2 to 5.

"Convert curves to Bézier curves" enables the transformation of Bézier
curves.

@{b}WARNING: Depending on the settings and the complexity of the picture 
and Amiga® system, this conversion can take a lot of time. Please you
should not be irritated if the @{"progress indicator" link WIN_PROGRESS } shows 0% for a long
period. This can not be changed for the moment, or the slow processing will
become even slower.@{ub}

The "Max. aberration"-gadget sets the aberration of the traced curve vs.
the original curve. The aberration is measured in pixels. A value of 2 to 5
gives best results. Higher values accelerate the conversion but is less
accurate. Lower values take much more time and the picture becomes bigger
in size.

The "Max. length of part of curves"-gadget sets the length of lines of
the object to be converted to a Bézier curve. A lower value (1 to 5) gives
best results.

I suggest, to try some different parameters, because of the result is hard
to estimate with the parameters only.

@{b}Notice: Bézier curves are not availabe for fonts.

Michiel den Outer (author of Navigator Titler, ...) has tested some settings
for Slope, which produces good results for pictures/fonts which shall be 
exported as 'NTitler Logo' or 'NTitler Font'. These settings are :

Min. correlation                = 20 %
Correlation accuracy            = 5
Convert to lines                = Checked
Tolerance                       = 3
Min. length of lines            = 2
Convert curves to Bézier curves = not checked
@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FLIP "Flip"
@{b}@{u}Flip@{uu}@{ub}

The submenue of this menue contains functions to flip the active picture
(bitmap or vector, depends on menue) picture on its @{"horizontal" link MENU_FLIPHOR } or
@{"vertical" link MENU_FLIPVER} axis. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FLIPHOR " Horizontal"
@{b}@{u}Flip / Horizontal@{uu}@{ub}

Flips the active picture (bitmap or vector, depends on menue) on its
horizontal axis.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_FLIPVER " Vertical"
@{b}@{u}Flip / Vertical@{uu}@{ub}

Flips the active picture (bitmap or vector, depends on menue) on its
vertical axis.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_ROTATE "Rotate"
@{b}@{u}Rotate@{uu}@{ub}

Rotates the vector picture either in 2 or 3 dimensions.

"Around X", "Around Y" and "Around Z" sets the angle the picture should be
rotated. The angle is given in degree and ranges from -180° ... 180°.


                         Z-axis |
                                |
                                |
                                |
                                |
                                |
                                |
                                *------- Y-axis
                               /
                              /
                             /
                            /
                        X-axis

The right quarter of the options-window represents a rectangle with the
same proportons as the to be rotated picture. The folded corner represents
the right, upper corner of the picture.

"Enlarge picture for better results" allows you the enlarge the vector
picture if it's to small. This will give better results, because of
roundness errors when rotating the picture. The real size of the picture
will be unchanged.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_DRAWINBITMAP "Draw vectors into bitmap"
@{b}@{u}Draw vectors into bitmap@{uu}@{ub}

This function is the inversation of Trace. Herewith you can convert a
vector picture into a bitmap picture.

With the gadgets you can select the size of the bitmap picture to create
in pixels (absolute) or in percent.

If "LockAspect" is enabled, then the @{"aspect" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } of picture will not be
changed when scaled.

@{b}WARNING: The bitmap picture to create needs, depend on its size, much 
memory.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETGUI "GUI"
@{b}@{u}GUI@{uu}@{ub}

Here you can change the @{"GUI" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-settings of XTrace.
With "Screen mode" you change the ScreenMode and with "Screen font" the
font.

XTrace needs at least a screen resolution of 640 x 400 pixels and a minimum
depth of 3 bit (8 colors). A non-proportional font is necessary too. If you
use more colors, the pictures in the @{"Picture windows" link WIN_PICTURE} can be displayed with
better contrast in grayscales. If you use CyberGraphX or Picasso96, you can
also choose screens with a larger depth than 8. The pictures in the
@{"Picture windows" link WIN_PICTURE} will then be displayed colored.

"Change Palette" enables you to @{"change" link WIN_EDITGUIPAL } the first 4 colors of the XTrace
screen and the color of the @{"frame" link WIN_TOOLS } tool. The other colors of the color
palette are used for the grayscale display.

@{b}If you change the ScreenMode or ScreenFont, XTrace closes all open 
windows and screens and reopens them with the new settings. If problems
(above all memory shortage) occur during this process, the actual picture
will be released WITHOUT ANY confirmation. Only change these settings if
there are no important unsaved picture windows open. If there is a shortage
of chip memory, no requester can be opened.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETPERMWINS "Permanent Windows"
@{b}@{u}Permanent Windows@{uu}@{ub}

Sets the positions of the permanently opened windows
(@{"Loaded pictures list window" link MENU_LOADEDPL }, @{"Pen display window" link MENU_PENDISPLAY }, @{"Log window" link MENU_LOG},
@{"Tools window" link WIN_TOOLS }).

The "Place" gadget sets the position where the selected window should appear
on the screen while opening. If "Find free area" is checked, XTrace will try
to find a free area on the screen to open the window. With "User defined" you
can define the window coordinates by x and y values.

For sizable windows the size can be set with the "Width" and "Height" Gadgets.
If "Open at start" is set then this window will open automatically at the
selected position on XTrace startup.

With "Get dimensions and position from screen" it is possible to read the
values of the open window into the settings.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETPICDISP "Picture Display"
@{b}@{u}Picture Display@{uu}@{ub}

This menue sets the screen to be used with @{"Display gray" link MENU_DISPGRAY }, @{"Display color" link MENU_DISPCOLOR },
@{"Display selected area gray" link MENU_DISPSGRAY} and @{"Display selected area color" link MENU_DISPSCOLOR}. 

There are no program-conditionally restrictions regarding to the screen
size, but the depth ist restricted to be between 2 and 8, because of XTrace
need free colors for the background pattern and XTrace only works with
pictures with 256 colors at maximum and therefore displaying with more
than 256 colors (for example CyberGfx) makes no sense.

If the picture to display don't use all available colors, the screen fall
back automatically to a lower depth, contingently also to depth 1, if the
picture always contain the colors for the background.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETGRAY "Gray Calculate Type"
@{b}@{u}Gray Calculate Type@{uu}@{ub}

With this menue you set the method to be used to calculate the color to
grayscale conversion.
The settings are used in the following windows or menues:
@{"Picture-Windows" link WIN_PICTURE}, @{"Display gray" link MENU_DISPGRAY}-screen, @{"Display selected area gray" link MENU_DISPSGRAY}-screen 
and for the @{"conversion" link MENU_CONVCOLOR } of color to grayscale pictures.

The "Gray calc type"-gadget sets the maximum value of the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } setting
or if a userdefined value should be used if a color is converted to gray.

A userdefined value can range from 1 ... 10000. There are 2 predefined
values (luminance and average).

This method was necessary because it is difficult to display a picture
with maximums or values. So you can choose between the 2 methods. If e.g. a
picture is made only of bluescales, it is nearly impossible to display it
with "luminance", but not with "maximum".
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETMONITOR "Monitor dimensions"
@{b}@{u}Monitor dimensions@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item sets the size of your monitor. Later this values will
be used for other purposes like the calculation of the real picture size.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETICONS "Icons"
@{b}@{u}Icons@{uu}@{ub}

Tells XTrace to save its files with ot without an icon. The icons are in
the PROGDIR:Icons directory as defxt_#?.info (where #? stands for the file
type).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETPATHPATT "Paths & Patterns"
@{b}@{u}Path & Patterns@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith, all paths and patterns, used by XTrace can be defined.

All paths and patterns are displayed in the Listview-Gadget ('Guides' and
'Temporary files' does not have a pattern, because of using without user-
interaction).

If you select an entry of this Listview-Gadget, the path and, if available,
the pattern is displayed in the gadgets below and you can edit it.

You can also select the path with a DirectoryRequester, selectable with
the gadget left of the 'Path' gadget.

Internally, XTrace uses two different lists : The first list, you can
change only in this window, contains all paths, also for the guide and
temporary files (@{"Main settings" link MENU_MAINSETT }) and the second list can only
be changed via the filerequesters (this means, the last path and pattern,
used in a filerequester were stored and used again, if you call up the
requester again (@{"Temp settings" link MENU_TEMPSETT })).

These two lists can be transfered into each other with the gadgets
"Get from filerequesters" and "Set to filerequesters". Previously setted
values will be overwritten.

Please note the following :

On startup, XTrace @{b}always@{ub} loads the settings form the PROGDIR:Settings,
because of the settings are at this time unloaded, this means, XTrace don't
known, if you have selected an other path.

Best is to set the path for the temporary files (above all if you use
@{"XPK" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY}-packed files) to your harddisk, because these files are unpacked to 
the RAM disk, and if you use RAM: as temporary file these files are 2 times
in memory.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETSAVEPACK "Save packer"
@{b}@{u}Save packer@{uu}@{ub}

Here you have the possibility to @{"choose" link WIN_SETXPK } the packer to be used when or not
when saving graphic files.

IFF ILBM and IFF XTVF files can use their own internal packer (ByteRun1).
These IFF ILBM files can be read by any Amiga® paint program.

All file types and appendant packers are displayed in the Listview-Gadget.
If you select an entry of this Listview-Gadget, the packer is displayed
in the gadgets below and you can edit it.

You can @{"select" link WIN_SETXPK } the @{"XPK" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-packer with the PopUp gadgets at right if you have
selected the 'PackType' XPK before, the selected packer will be display left
beside.

Before using XPK-packer please read the chapter @{"Paths & Patterns" link MENU_SETPATHPATT }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETIOBUFFER "File I/O buffers"
@{b}@{u}File I/O buffers@{uu}@{ub}

Sets the decrunch-buffer size to be used when loading IFF ILBM files.
You can set a fixed size for this buffer or use the buffer always,
independently of it's size.

You can also set an I/O buffer for any file operations. If you often save
on disk you should make the buffer larger. Standard is 20 kB.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETAI "Adobe Illustrator®"
@{b}@{u}Adobe Illustrator®@{uu}@{ub}

The Adobe Illustrator® format is opposite to the EPS format expanded with some
capabilities, which are stored in so called ProcSets. These ProcSets can be
included directly in the AI file or can be requested at loading from the loading
program. With the Checkbox gadget "Include Adobe Illustrator® ProcSets into
file" you can choose if you want to include theses ProcSets into the file
(gadget checked) or not. If you don't include the ProcSets, the resulting file
will be at little bit smaller (~ 16 Kb), but it can only be displayed by
programs which contains the needed ProcSets (for example PageStream). If you
include the ProcSets, it can be normally interpreted as EPS file and can be
displayed, for example, also by the HWGPost datatype.

If "Write outlines only" is selected, only the outlines of the objects will
be written e.g. the objects will be unfilled. If these option is selected,
you can additional select the "Thickness" of the outlines, measured in 1/720
inch and/or select if you want to use only black for the outlines.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETDXF2D "DXF 2D"
@{b}@{u}DXF 2D@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can define the resolution of the @{"DXF 2D" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS} file.

With "Density" you can select the resolution in DPI or if you select
"Use DPI value of vector picture", you'll use the orginal DPI value
of the concerning picture.

When you select "Use pen 1 only", only pen 1 will be used in the DXF files,
e.g. all lines will be same colored.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETDXF3D "DXF 3D"
@{b}@{u}DXF 3D@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can set the maximum size (width or height, depending of the 
picture) and the thickness (depth) of the @{"DXF 3D" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS} object, which you can create 
with the function @{"Export picture" link MENU_EXPORTPIC} out of traced pictures.

XTrace fits the the picture of the font at a box of the defined size, ie. the
largest size of your picture (width or height) has a size in the file of the
defined size. So you can estimate the relation of the size and thickness of
the object.

Additional, you can select, whether the 3D object shall have 2 dimensions 
only, ie. it should be plain or not. If the 3D object shall have 3 dimensions
("Plain object" off) you can select additionally, which of the 3 'sides'
shall be written (Front, Back, Sides). At least one of this option must
be active. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETEPS "EPS"
@{b}@{u}EPS@{uu}@{ub}

Here you define the size and number of colors to be used by the @{"EPSI" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS}- and
@{"EPSB" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS}-preview-picture.

If "Write outlines only" is selected, only the outlines of the objects will
be written e.g. the objects will be unfilled. If these option is selected, 
you can additional select the "Thickness" of the outlines, measured in 1/720 
inch and/or select if you want to use only black for the outlines.

You can select with "Use CRLF instead of LF only" the termination of saved
text lines. Either LF only (AmigaDOS, UNIX) or with CRLF (MS-DOS) is
possible.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETFIG "FIG"
@{b}@{u}FIG@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can intend, if you want to fill ("Write outlines only" off) the 
objects of the exported picture as @{"FIG" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS} file or not. If not, you can also
specify the thickness of the outlines in 1/80 inch.

In addition you can intend, if you want to export the colors of the picture
normally or as grayscales. If you've choosed the outline mode, you can also 
choose the 3. possibility "Use black only for outline drawings" which allows,
to save outlines/outcurves as black outlines/outcurves, independently of their
orginal color.

Because of the FIG format uses 32 predefined colors, you can choose with the
gadget "Use predefined FIG colors" whether you want to use these colors for
colors of the traced picture. If yes, you can choose the maximum allowed ab-
erration between picture color and fitest predefined FIG color with the gadget
"Max. aberration". This aberration is measured in percent as to the diagonal
of space of the RGB cube.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETNTITLER "Navigator Titler"
@{b}@{u}Navigator Titler@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can set the maximum size (width or height, depending of the 
picture resp. the biggest char), the thickness (depth) and the resolution
of the @{"Navigator Titler Logos/Fonts" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS}, which you can create with the function
@{"Export picture" link MENU_EXPORTPIC} out of traced pictures/fonts.

XTrace fits the the picture/chars of the font at a box of the defined size,
ie. the largest size of your picture/font (width or height) has a size in the
logo/font of the defined size. So you can estimate the relation of the size and
thickness of the logo/font.

Additional you can set the size of triangles to create to limited or
unlimited. This size is measured in "Square-units" and is related to
the setted maximal size. The smaller this value is, the smaller are the 
triangles which will be created (important for NTitler's explosions),
but the larger the file size and calculation time will be.

See @{"FAQ" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FAQ} also.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETMEMORY "Memory"
@{b}@{u}Memory@{uu}@{ub}

This menue item tells XTrace how much memory the program should not
allocate and if/when an alert requester should tell you that too much
memory is used. This way you still have memory used by background
processes.

XTrace also can flush the memory and release unused libraries, devices etc.
if memory gets low.

Hint: set reserved memory to 100 kB, alert limit to 200 kB and flush on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETSTORTYPE "Bitmap storage type"
@{b}@{u}Bitmap storage type@{uu}@{ub}

XTrace can store the bitmap of a loaded picture using 3 different types
into RAM (Planar, Chunky and ByteMap; explanation at the @{"Glossary" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }).

Thereby its possible (with using more RAM per picture) process pictures
with the type Chunky or ByteMap faster than this ones with the type Planar.

Please note, the processing of Chunky or ByteMap is faster, but the loading
and saving will become slower because of converting into / out of these
formats. But this is no real disadvantage, because of you don't load/save
permanently and the transformation is fast with a fast processor.

The possible settings :

With "Storage type" you can set the storage type (Planar/Chunky/ByteMap).
If you choose "Best", XTrace determins that type, wasting 10 % of allocated
memory at maximum stipulated by unused bits, but anyhow the fastest.

If you have much memory, unused anyhow while XTrace runs, select "ByteMap"
and "Fall back ..." (see below) for any cases.

With "Fall back ..." you can define, whether XTrace should fall back to a
storage type of lower memory consumption if it can't allocate the defined
type.

This option is not available at type = Planar, because of the advantages
of this type, working with less memory and small cohere memory blocks.
This options should be used everytime (if you don't use Planar).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETBANKS "Vector/ Object banks"
@{b}@{u}Vector / Object banks@{uu}@{ub}

XTrace manages objects and vectors dynamic based on the principle of banks,
means objects and vectors are stored in banks with fixed size, which will
be allocated when they are needed. If the number of banks is to low, more
will be automatically allocated.

You can set the number of banks and the banksize for objects and vectors
separately.

These values are only limited by available memory and can be set
independently from each other. Take care not to use unlogical values, which
uses a lot of memory (e.g. some but large banks or many but small banks).
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETGENERAL "General"
@{b}@{u}General@{uu}@{ub}

Sets the general settings / features of XTrace.

The "Undo" function allows you to get back the last processing step of
XTrace. This function should always be enabled, unless you have an
Amiga® system with low memory.

"AppIcon" puts the XTrace-AppIcon (Application Icon) on the Workbench. If
you drag and drop picture-icons on this AppIcon, the picture will be loaded
in XTrace. Or if you doubleclick this icon, the XTrace screen will pop to
front. The AppIcon is defined in "PROGDIR:Icons/defxt_AppIcon.info".

With "Save temp settings at exit" you tell XTrace to automatically save,
eventually changed temporary settings (the paths and patterns of the file
requesters and global operator settings), when leaving XTrace.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SETDEFVALS "Default Values"
@{b}@{u}Default Values@{uu}@{ub}

Here you set the standard values, to be used by XTrace, if these values
should be missing when loading files.

At the moment only the DPI-value for IFF ILBM files can be set.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_MAINSETT "Main settings"
@{b}@{u}Main settings@{uu}@{ub}

The settings of XTrace are divided into Main settings and Temp settings.

The Main settings hold all values you can change in the Settings-menue.
The Temp settings hold all values which occur or change during work with
XTrace. e.g. actual paths and patterns in requesters and global operator
settings.

The submenues of the Main settings menue allows you to reset the settings
to default (Reset to default), load (Load ...) new settings or replace
(Save) the original settings file or save (Save as...) it with a new name.

If you do a "Reset to default" all settings will be reset, including those
for screen and windows (these will reopen). (also check @{"GUI" link MENU_SETGUI })

@{b}Please note, that the file format of the settings has been changed
with XTrace v2.00. Please read the @{"history" LINK XTrace_Appendix.guide/HISTORY} for more information.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_TEMPSETT "Temp settings"
@{b}@{u}Temp settings@{uu}@{ub}

The settings of XTrace are divided into Main settings and Temp settings.

The Main settings hold all values you can change in the Settings-menue.
The Temp settings hols all values which occur or change during work with
XTrace. e.g. actual paths and patterns in requesters and global operator
settings.

The submenues of the Temp settings menue allows you to reset the settings
to default (Reset to default), load (Load ...) new settings or replace
(Save) the original settings file or save (Save as...) it with a new name.

@{b}Please note, that the file format of the settings has been changed
with XTrace v2.00. Please read the @{"history" LINK XTrace_Appendix.guide/HISTORY} for more information.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE MENU_SAVEALLSETT "Save all settings"
@{b}@{u}Save all settings@{uu}@{ub}

This menue saves both settings, Main settings and Temp settings.
It just resumes the submenues "Save" of @{"Main settings" link MENU_MAINSETT } and @{"Temp settings" link MENU_TEMPSETT }.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOWS "2.3 Windows"
@{b}@{u}2.3 Windows@{uu}@{ub}

These windows are available in XTrace :

Background-Windows (they run in async mode, you can continue your work
with XTrace, if these windows are open):

 @{"Tools                          " link WIN_TOOLS } Toolbox
 @{"Loaded pictures list           " link MENU_LOADEDPL } List of loaded pictures
 @{"Log window                     " link MENU_LOG } Log window
 @{"Pen display                    " link MENU_PENDISPLAY } Pen display

Information windows :

 @{"About XTrace                   " link MENU_ABOUTXTRACE } About XTrace
 @{"Info                           " link MENU_INFO } Informations
 @{"Progress                       " link WIN_PROGRESS } Progress display

Requester windows :

 @{"Choose filetype to export      " link WIN_CHOOSETOEXPORT } Choose File Type
 @{"Choose pen                     " link WIN_CHOOSEPEN } Choose Pen
 @{"Choose color                   " link WIN_CHOOSECOLOR} Choose color
 @{"Choose grayscale               " link WIN_CHOOSEGRAYSCALE} Choose grayscale
 @{"Color names                    " link WIN_COLORNAMES } Color name
 @{"Clipboard                      " link WIN_CLIPBOARD } Access Clipboard

Operator windows :

 @{"Convert color                  " link MENU_CONVCOLOR } Convert Color-Types
 @{"Coalesce colors                " link MENU_COALESCECOLORS} Coalescing of resembling colors

 @{"Display histograms             " link MENU_DISPHISTO } Display histograms
 @{"Edit palette                   " link MENU_EDITPICPAL } edit color palette
 @{"Global color control           " link MENU_GLOBCOLCON } Edit colors global

 @{"Adaptive histogram equalization" link MENU_ADAPTHISTEQUAL } Adaptive histogram equalization

 @{"Scale                          " link MENU_SCALE } Scale picture
 @{"Border process                 " link MENU_BORDER } Remove/add border

 @{"Apply digital filter seq.      " link MENU_FILTERSEQ } Apply digital filter seq.
 @{"Edit filter                    " link WIN_EDITFILTER } Edit digital filter
 @{"Thinning                       " link MENU_THINNING } Thinning
 @{"Edge detection                 " link MENU_EDGEDETECT } Edge detection
 @{"Edge enhancement               " link MENU_EDGEENHANCE } Edge enhancement
 @{"Remove isolated pixels         " link MENU_REMISOLATEDPIXELS} Remove isolated pixels

 @{"Change aspect                  " link MENU_CHASPECT } Change aspect
 @{"Change DPI & real sizes        " link MENU_CHDPI } Change DPI and picture size

 @{"Trace                          " link MENU_TRACE } Trace

 @{"Fill selected area             " link MENU_FILLSELAREA } Fill selected area

 @{"Make pen transparent           " link MENU_MAKEPENTRANS } Make pen transparent
 @{"Remove pen                     " link MENU_REMOVEPEN } Remove pen

 @{"Supress noise                  " link MENU_SUPNOISE } Supress noise
 @{"Slope                          " link MENU_SLOPE } Slope

 @{"Rotate                         " link MENU_ROTATE } Rotate 3D

 @{"Draw vectors into bitmap       " link MENU_DRAWINBITMAP } Draw vectors into bitmap

Settings windows :

 @{"GUI                            " link MENU_SETGUI } GUI settings
 @{"Permanent windows              " link MENU_SETPERMWINS } Permanent windows
 @{"Picture display                " link MENU_SETPICDISP } Picture Display settings
 @{"Gray calculate type            " link MENU_SETGRAY } Gray calculate type
 @{"Monitor dimensions             " link MENU_SETMONITOR } Monitor dimensions

 @{"Icons                          " link MENU_SETICONS } Icons
 @{"Paths & Patterns               " link MENU_SETPATHPATT } Paths & patterns
 @{"Save packer                    " link MENU_SETSAVEPACK } Packer-settings
 @{"File I/O buffers               " link MENU_SETIOBUFFER } File buffer

 @{"Adobe Illustrator®             " link MENU_SETAI} AI-settings
 @{"DXF 2D                         " link MENU_SETDXF2D } DXF 2D-settings
 @{"DXF 3D                         " link MENU_SETDXF3D } DXF 3D-settings
 @{"EPS                            " link MENU_SETEPS } EPS-settings
 @{"FIG                            " link MENU_SETFIG } FIG-settings
 @{"Navigator Titler               " link MENU_SETNTITLER} NTitler-settings

 @{"Memory                         " link MENU_SETMEMORY } Memory-settings

 @{"Bitmap storage type            " link MENU_SETSTORTYPE } Bitmap storage type
 @{"Vector / Object banks          " link MENU_SETBANKS } Vector / Object banks

 @{"General                        " link MENU_SETGENERAL } General
 @{"Default values                 " link MENU_SETDEFVALS } Default values

 @{"XPK                            " link WIN_SETXPK } XPK settings
 @{"Edit palette                   " link WIN_EDITGUIPAL } Edit color palette

Export windows :

 @{"DXF 3D                         " link WIN_EXPNFONT } Export DXF 3D
 @{"Navigator Titler Font          " link WIN_EXPNFONT } Export Navigator Titler Font
 @{"Navigator Titler Logo          " link WIN_EXPNLOGO } Export Navigator Titler Logo

Picture-Window :

 @{"Picture                        " link WIN_PICTURE } Picture-window

@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_TRACE "Trace window"
@{b}@{u}Trace window@{uu}@{ub}

This window shows the trace-process:

The upper part of the window shows how the picture is being traced or a
message, that this option is disabled. Below you see the filename, the size
and actual number of @{"objects" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } and @{"vectors" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY}. The lower part shows the process
bars of the different tracing processes.

"Pause" stops the process temporarly (to continue press "Pause" again).
"Abort" cancels the process completely.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_PICTURE "Picture window"
@{b}@{u}Picture window@{uu}@{ub}

Each of these windows displays a picture. If the window-name shows this
(example):

 [1] - X(-) LAGear.XTVF

it has the following meaning (from left to right):

"1"    - Number of the window (used internally by XTrace). At the moment a
         maximum of 50 opened windows at the same time is possible.

"-"    - The picture has not been changed since it has been loaded. Any
         change in the picture converts the "-" to "*".

"X(-)" - This text can be occured multiple times. If there is a "B" instead of
         the "X" a bitmap picture is present, a "V" means a vector picture is
         present. The "-" means this picture part has not been changed since
         it has been loaded. Any change in the picture part converts the "-"
         to "*".

"LA.." - The name of the loaded file.

The picture windows has horizontal and vertical scrollbars. This way the
picture can be scrolled, if it doesn't fit inside the picture windows
(@{"Tools-Window" link WIN_TOOLS }).

With the size-gadget you change the size of the window. The close-gadget
@{"closes" link MENU_CLOSEPIC} the window. 

With the cycle gadget left above you can switch between the bitmap picture
and the vector picture, can also be done with the <Return> key.
Is there only one of two possible pictures, this gadget is disabled.

The info line beside the cycle gadget shows the @{"Color-Type" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }, the size in
pixels, the depth, the number of pens and the actual magnification (can be
changed with the @{"magnifier" link WIN_TOOLS } tool) of the bitmap picture.

If the vector picture is displayed, the size in pixels, the number of objects
and vectors and the number of used pens and the actual magnification
(can be changed with the @{"magnifier" link WIN_TOOLS } tool) are displayed.

The method used to calculate the grayscales to use can be changed in
@{"Settings" link MENU_SETGRAY}. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_CHOOSETOEXPORT "Choose filetype to export"
@{b}@{u}Choose filetype to export@{uu}@{ub}

In this window the @{"file format" LINK XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FORMATS} can be set (depends which submenue is
choosen: bitmap / vector / export / export to clipboard) with the
"Filetype"-Listviewgadget.
You can also set which packer type to use with the "Packtype"-Cyclegadget :

 - none         file will not be packed

 - ByteRun1     internal packer, can only be used with IFF ILBM and IFF
                XTVF files

 - XPK          use one of the external @{"XPK" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-packers,
                which must be @{"set" link WIN_SETXPK }. You can not use XPK
                when accessing the clipboard.

If the file type allows extra settings, these can be changed with the
"Settings"-Buttongadget.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_TOOLS "Tools window"
@{b}@{u}Tools window@{uu}@{ub}

This window is the Toolbox for all open @{"Picture windows" link WIN_PICTURE }.
Here is an explanation of the differnt symbols:

Arrow      - Normal mouse pointer, is not a tool.

             This tool can also be activated with the <p> key. 
 
Eyedropper - If you move the eyedropper (while the left mouse button is
             pressed) over the picture, you can see infos in the 
             @{"PenDisplay-Window" link MENU_PENDISPLAY} about the color under the eyedropper.

             This tool can also be activated with the <e> key. 

Frame      - the mouse pointer is now a cross. It is used to draw a frame
             in the picture window. If this window already contains a frame
             it will be deletes. The frame has little squares in each
             corner and in the middle of each side. If the arrow of the
             toolbox is used to click these squares (left mouse button
             pressed) the frame behaves as if it had scroll/slider or size
             gadgets. The frame can be resized to your wish. If you click
             @{b}inside@{ub} the frame with the arrow tool you can move the
             frame. The frame can be deleted by pressing the <DEL> key,

             This tool can also be activated with the <m> key. 

             The frame is used to @{"copy" link MENU_COPYSELAREA } or @{"fill" link MENU_FILLSELAREA } parts of the picture.

Magnifier  - this mouse pointer allows you magnify the picture twice if you
             press the left mouse button. Pressing it again enlarges the
             picture again twice its size etc. The right mouse button
             reduces the picture by a factor of 2 (half size) etc.
             (WARNING: the menues doesn't work yet !!!) The middle mouse
             button or the <Space>-key displays the picture in its original
             size again.

             This tool can also be activated with the <z> key. 

             You can use the scroll-bars to move the picture if the picture
             is magnified.

             If you select another tool, the menue is available anew.

Hand       - This mouse pointer allows you to move around a magnified
             picture (click inside the picture, press the left mouse button
             and move the mouse).

             This tool can also be activated with the <d> key. 

All available tools can be cycled through with the <TAB> key forwardly and
with <Shift> + <TAB> backwardly.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_SETXPK "XPK settings"
@{b}@{u}XPK settings@{uu}@{ub}

In this window you can change the settings of the actual packer mode. The
@{"XPK" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY}-packer can be changed with the "packer" -Listviewgadget (only those
XPK-packers are shown which use loss-free compression and no encryption). 
The name, full length name, description and the packer mode description are
displayed.

Please note, the displayed pack- and depack speeds are not related to the
current system but they are average speeds of an A3000 system (MC68030
25 MHz). This means, the speed can differ, depends on your system.

Please read the documentation of the XPK package. It's available on Aminet.

If the packer is changed, the default mode setting for this mode is used.

XTrace can read and save XPK-packed files, as long as the packer is known
to the system and the file format of the packed file is compatible with
XTrace.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_CHOOSEPEN "Choose pen"
@{b}@{u}Choose pen@{uu}@{ub}

In this window you can select a needed pen for a active operator.

At top you can see the active pen, below the "Defined pen"-gadget, where-
with you can select pens from interesting picture parts (All corners, the
most used pen and the pen, possibly selected before with the @{"eyedropper" link WIN_TOOLS }
tool). Below this gadget are listed all pens with grayscales, which you can
select also. Right this palette are the respective @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }.- and @{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY } values
of the actual pen.

At the bottom, the real color and the name of the color, as it is available
from the internal list, are displayed. This list only contains a range of
colors/names, as this list can not include all existing colors. The Match-
value tells you how similar the shown colorname matches the real color.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_CHOOSECOLOR "Choose color"
@{b}@{u}Choose color@{uu}@{ub}

In this window you can select a needed color for a active operator.

The colorwheel and the gradientslider are used to change the color according 
to the @{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

The 3 sliders "Red", "Green" and "Blue" are used to change the color according
to the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

With "Get color from picture palette" you can choose a color of the palette of
the currently processed picture.

At the right, the real color, their representation as gray value and the name
of the color, as it is available from the internal list, are displayed. This
list only contains a range of colors/names, as this list can not include all
existing colors. The Matchvalue tells you how similar the shown colorname 
matches the real color.


@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_CHOOSEGRAYSCALE "Choose grayscale"
@{b}@{u}Choose grayscale@{uu}@{ub}

In this window you can select a needed grayscale for a active operator.

The slider "Gray" is used to change the grayscale. At the bottom, the
grayscale is displayed.

With "Get grayscale from picture palette" you can choose a grayscale of the
palette of the currently processed picture.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_COLORNAMES "Color names"
@{b}@{u}Color names@{uu}@{ub}

XTrace contains a list of about 400 color values with their names. In this
window you can choose a color from this name list.
On the left side are the names, on the right side are the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }.- and
@{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY} values. Below right is the color and the grayscale. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_EDITGUIPAL "Edit palette"
@{b}@{u}Edit palette@{uu}@{ub}

Is used to edit the colors of the XTrace-screen.

The palettegadget (above right) is used to change the active pen.

The gadgets below "Copy", "Swap" are used to copy and swap pens. The
"Reset" gadget resets @{b}all@{ub} the pens to their default colors.

The colorwheel and the gradientslider are used to change the colors of the
active pen according to the @{"HSB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

The 3 sliders "Red", "Green" and "Blue" in the middle of the window are
used to change the colors of the active pen according to the @{"RGB" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }-colormodel.

"Name" is the name of the color, like it is used in th internal list. The
Match-value tells you how similar the shown colorname matches the real color.

The PopUp-gadget besides the name opens a requester window with all available
colornames (@{"Color names" link WIN_COLORNAMES }).

Please note :

Pens 0 .. 3 are the colors of the @{"GUI" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }, pen 4 is the color of the
@{"frame" link WIN_TOOLS} tool. 
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_PROGRESS "Progress"
@{b}@{u}Progress@{uu}@{ub}

This window dispalys the progress of an operation.
"Pause" temporarly stops the process (press "Pause" again to continue) and
"Abort" cancels the process.

It is possible that during lengthy operations, the "Pause" and "Abort"
gadget react with a certain delay, This won't be changed as otherwise
XTrace would slow down.

The progress bar also show its status in percent. Additional, the
current time and the time used by the operator will be display.
If the the operation is (approximately) linear the necessary time
and the finish time are shown too else only "--:--:--" is displayed
(non-linear operation).

The time format is Hours:Minutes:Seconds.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_CLIPBOARD "Clipboard"
@{b}@{u}Clipboard@{uu}@{ub}

A kind of file requester for the @{"clipboards" link XTrace_Appendix.guide/GLOSSARY }.

The Listviewgadget shows all 256 clipboards, with Unit-number, Loadable,
Type, Size in bytes and its Name. XTrace can load the clipboard if L
(Loadable) is marked with a "*",

It is possble to specify the to be loaded Unit with the number-gadget and
the unit-number.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_EDITFILTER "Edit filter"
@{b}@{u}Edit filter@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can create own filters and filter sets or display and change
supplied filters/filter sets. For further information about digital filters and
terms please read the chapter about @{"digital filter sequences" link MENU_FILTERSEQ}.

The gadgets :

The two boxes on the top contains data and control elements for filter sets.
Here you can set a name and a comment for filter sets ("Filter set name" and
"Filter set remark" gadgets). The gadgets below you can use to manage filter
sets. With "Index" you can go through the single filters. "Add" and "Insert"
adds/insert single empty filters into the filterset, with "Remove" you can
remove single filters from the set. "Cut", "Copy" and "Paste" have the same
functionality like in a normal editor. With help of "Filter resul calculation
type" you can set, how XTrace calculates the result out of the results of the
single filters. "Minimum" chooses the darkest value, "Maximum" the brightest and
"Euclidean distance" the distance of all results.
@{b}Caution: A filterset contains at least 2 single filters, that means one single
filter will here not be treated as filterset, so some gadgets are disabled.@{ub}

With the gadgets in the other boxes you can edit all filters. In case of a
filterset, they only affect the filter choosen with the "Index" gadget :

The actual filter type (linear/non-linear) be changed with "Type"-gadget.
If you change the filter type from linear to non-linear and the matrix
contains values different from 0 or 1, then a requester pops up asking to
change the matrix, as a non-linear matrix can contain values equal 0 or
1 only. If you click "Ok", all values different from 0 or 1 will be
converted to 1.

Below, the filter matrix, containing weights, is shown. The weights are integer
in a range from approximately -2 Mrd. (-2 * 10^9) to +2 Mrd. (2 * 10^9).

The 2 gadgets below the matrix are usable for mirroring and rotating the weights
of the matrix. To use one of the operators (Mirror: The 'line' after "Mirror" is
the mirror axis) you choose the operator and click "Perform". This kind of
processing the filter matrix is very helpful for creating filter sets or editing
direction depend filters.

The filter size can be changed with the "Size"-gadget. With the "Shape" gadget
you can select one of the base-shape of the filter. The "Optimize" gadget 
checks the filter and sets the size and shape so that all values different
from 0 will be used.

"Clear unused elements" sets all values to 0, which are outside the defined
matrix size.

Of course it is possible to name, save and load the defined filter resp.
filterset. Additional remarks can be stored with the "Remark" gadget.

At @{b}linear filters@{ub} you can set also the needed divider (normally the
sum of all weights) and the bias. The gadget "Calculate" calculates these both
values. A divider equal 0 is not possible/allowed. The calculation method
depends on the value of the "Mode" gadget. At the "Standard" mode, the
"Divider" will be calculated only. It will be choosen so, that while filtering
the weighted average will be calculated. At the "Enhanced" mode both values
will be choosen so, that all results are in the normal color range and no
clipping is needed.

At @{b}non-linear filters@{ub} you can select the rank (Minimum/Median/
Maximum) with the "Rank" gadget.

@{b}Please note, that the file format of the filters has been changed with
XTrace v2.00. Please read the @{"history" LINK XTrace_Appendix.guide/HISTORY} or @{"'FileFormatConverter'" LINK FILEFORMATCONVERTER} for more
information.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_EXPNFONT "Export Navigator Titler Font"
@{b}@{u}Export Navigator Titler Font@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can enable/disable the char groups you want to include into
your Navigator Font. This can safe memory and disk space, because of Amiga
fonts can contain many chars which you will not or rarely need.

All chars are seperated into 8 groups, which you can select with the appendant
checkbox gadgets :

@{b}Upper characters@{ub}

All general upper characters ('A' - 'Z').

@{b}Lower characters@{ub}

All general lower characters ('a' - 'z').

@{b}National upper characters@{ub}

All national upper characters, which are not used by every language, like 'Ä',
'Ö', 'Ü', 'Ă', 'Ć', 'Č'.

@{b}National lower characters@{ub}

All national lower characters, which are not used by every language, like 'ä',
'ö', 'ü', 'ć', 'ç', 'č', 'é'.

@{b}Numerals@{ub}

The numerals '0' - '9'.

@{b}Punctuations@{ub}

Punctuations, brackets, additional characters, ... In general these chars,
which are included at the keyboard and are not characters or numerals.

@{b}Special characters@{ub}

Special characters in the ASCII code like 'ˇ', '˘', 'Ł', '¤', 'Ą'.

@{b}User definable characters@{ub}

User definable characters, which are normally undefined in Amiga fonts and can
be defined by the user with a font editor.

If the font contains no characters of a group, the appendent gadget will be
disabled. At least one group must be selected for exporting.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_EXPNLOGO "Export Navigator Titler Logo"
@{b}@{u}Export Navigator Titler Logo@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can set the pen of the objects of your picture, which you'll
export as 3D Navigator Titler Logo.

All 2D object with the selected pen will be written as 3D object, whereas
all other objects are considered as background, ie. invisible. 

See @{"FAQ" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FAQ} also.
@ENDNODE

@NODE WIN_EXPDXF3D "Export DXF 3D"
@{b}@{u}Export DXF 3D@{uu}@{ub}

Herewith you can set the pen of the objects of your picture, which you'll
export as 3D DXF object.

All 2D object with the selected pen will be written, whereas all other objects
are considered as background, ie. invisible. 

See @{"FAQ" link XTrace_Miscellaneous.guide/FAQ} also.
@ENDNODE

@NODE ONLINEHELP "2.4 Using Online-Help"
@{b}@{u}2.4 Using Online-Help@{uu}@{ub}

XTrace has a built-in help function that can pop up help on any window
or menu-item directly from the program. This function is activated when
activating a window or positioning the mouse-pointer over a menu-item and
then pressing the <HELP> key on your keyboard.

AmigaGuide is opened asynchronously, meaning that it will be launched as
separate task, independently from XTrace. This allows you to continue your
work while help is being displayed.

If you wish to select help on another object while AmigaGuide is open,
just activate the function like described above and AmigaGuide will show
the text on that object without you having to close it's window and load
everything again.

The latest versions of AmigaGuide allows you to save position, width and
height of the AmigaGuide-window. When the online help system is activated
later, AmigaGuide will open at the coordinates last saved. 

@{b}NOTE: In order for the online help system to work, 'amigaguide.library'
      must be available on your system, the right path has been set
      correctly in @{"Settings / Paths & Patterns" link MENU_SETPATHPATT} and a documentation of
      XTrace have to be installed.@{ub}
@ENDNODE

@NODE FILEFORMATCONVERTER "2.5 External program 'FileFormatConverter'"
@{b}@{u}2.5 External program 'FileFormatConverter'@{uu}@{ub}

With v2.00 of XTrace the fileformat of the filters (@{"Edit filter" LINK WIN_EDITFILTER}),
filtersequences (@{"Apply digital filter sequence" LINK MENU_FILTERSEQ}, colorcurves
(@{"Global color control" LINK MENU_GLOBCOLCON}) and settings (@{"Main settings" link MENU_MAINSETT}, @{"Temp settings" link MENU_TEMPSETT})
has been changed. Now, a more portable text format is used which is easy to extend.

In order to further use self created filters, filtersequences and colorcurves,
you must convert them with the program 'FileFormatConverter' which is included
in this distribution.

This program has a CLI and WB interface. If you start it from a CLI with one or
more files or patterns as argument it will convert the given files. If you
supply no name or if you start it from the WB it will open a file requester and
you can choose the files to convert.

'FileFormatConverter' doesn't overwrite the input files, it renames them into
#?.BAK files.

@{b}Please note that the settings files can't be converted. Therefore, Please set
your settings new and save them.@{ub}
@ENDNODE



